00:06:29.164 --> 00:06:32.035
NICK BUTCHER: Thanks very much
for that [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:32.035 --> 00:06:33.190
ROMAN NURIK: All right,
moving on.

00:06:33.190 --> 00:06:35.370
So the next step, and this
is one of the key

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:36.450
most important steps.

00:06:36.450 --> 00:06:39.810
This is, I think, one of the
key ways in which polished

00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:42.750
apps and apps with really good
fit and finish differentiate

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:45.530
from the less polished apps,
is the margins and the

00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:47.330
spacing, the way they
treat white space.

00:06:47.330 --> 00:06:51.760
And this is one of a UI
designer's best tools in

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:53.630
creating contrast
and readability.

00:06:53.630 --> 00:06:57.160
Readability is the concept of
not necessarily legibility of

00:06:57.160 --> 00:07:00.050
paragraphs and words, but
readability is the sense of,

00:07:00.050 --> 00:07:02.770
given a block of text, how
easy is it for the eye to

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:04.230
consume that information.

00:07:04.230 --> 00:07:06.560
And adding margins and
spaces is one of the

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:08.210
key ways to do that.

00:07:08.210 --> 00:07:11.850
So you notice that from that
previous screen, we've tweaked

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:17.450
the spacing so that you can
better separate each article

00:07:17.450 --> 00:07:20.410
in the list on the left from
its background and from the

00:07:20.410 --> 00:07:24.840
other articles, as well as we've
added some standard 16dp

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:29.410
margins throughout the content
on the detail screen here.

00:07:29.410 --> 00:07:32.320
ADAM KOCH: And you'll probably
hear us often mention the 48dp

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:35.360
rhythm from the design side, so
that's really what all of

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:37.360
this is based off.

00:07:37.360 --> 00:07:39.550
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, and we'll
show some red lines at the end

00:07:39.550 --> 00:07:41.780
that show some of the
spacings that we use

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:43.480
on tablets as well.

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:45.720
And this is, again, one of
the key ways in which you

00:07:45.720 --> 00:07:49.840
differentiate handset from
tablet to make sure that,

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:52.030
again, that readability,
that comfort in

00:07:52.030 --> 00:07:53.740
reading is still there.

00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:57.320
So let's move on unless,
Nick, you had any--

00:07:57.320 --> 00:07:57.520
NICK BUTCHER: No.

00:07:57.520 --> 00:07:59.453
It just instantly got more
breathing room, I think it's

00:07:59.453 --> 00:08:00.500
so much easier to stand now.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:02.140
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:06.250
So the next step is another
important way in which you can

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:10.420
introduce consistency and a
strong rhythm in your app is

00:08:10.420 --> 00:08:12.230
the way you treat photo
thumbnails.

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:15.470
So you'll notice that in the
previous version, these photos

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:18.750
were all jaggedy or lopsided.

00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:21.450
They didn't have a strong
rhythm, because they had

00:08:21.450 --> 00:08:22.950
different aspect ratios.

00:08:22.950 --> 00:08:28.500
So one of the ways in which you
can alleviate this is to

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:31.880
introduce a different type of
scaling, and Adam could talk

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:34.440
about that, but basically you'll
notice here that all

00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:35.580
the photos line up.

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:39.320
They're full bleed edge to edge,
and they introduce kind

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:44.130
of a strong, single line
in your design.

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:47.510
So it's very easy for the eye to
separate the text from the

00:08:47.510 --> 00:08:50.950
image, and to separate the
images from each other since

00:08:50.950 --> 00:08:53.090
there's kind of that light
separator there.

00:08:53.090 --> 00:08:55.300
ADAM KOCH: Yeah, and then from
the developer side, there's an

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:57.720
attribute scale type, which you
can set to center crop,

00:08:57.720 --> 00:09:00.620
where the framework will
actually do this for you.

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:04.330
Of course, if you're pulling
down an image from a server

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:06.610
side or something like that, you
could have the images come

00:09:06.610 --> 00:09:08.920
down at the right size already,
but in many cases

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:09.700
that's not possible.

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:11.980
So this is actually a really
good way to make sure that

00:09:11.980 --> 00:09:15.100
they're all lined up and
of the same size.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:15.790
I really like this.

00:09:15.790 --> 00:09:18.860
It really brings the images out
a little bit more, and as

00:09:18.860 --> 00:09:20.860
you say, the lines really
make a huge difference

00:09:20.860 --> 00:09:24.250
there on the left.

00:09:24.250 --> 00:09:25.910
NICK BUTCHER: The before version
where you have the

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:28.900
uneven raggedness, the edge is
like a jagged tooth pattern.

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:31.415
It looks like you have these
gappy teeth, and it just isn't

00:09:31.415 --> 00:09:32.790
right, [INAUDIBLE] very well.

00:09:32.790 --> 00:09:33.760
That is a big improvement.

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:34.480
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:09:34.480 --> 00:09:37.240
What you want to avoid is, if
you look at your design or

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:41.280
your UI from a few feet away,
you don't want to see a New

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:42.590
York City skyline.

00:09:42.590 --> 00:09:44.660
You want to see consistent
grids.

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:46.300
You want to see rectangular
grids.

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:49.670
And in some cases for really
complex, interesting UIs, you

00:09:49.670 --> 00:09:51.880
probably want to go just a
little deeper than that.

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:53.290
You want to do some more
interesting things.

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:55.780
But at the very most basic
level, if you're simply

00:09:55.780 --> 00:10:00.030
presenting a collection of
information, you want to make

00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:03.910
sure that you're establishing
a grid, and establishing

00:10:03.910 --> 00:10:07.220
single lines so that it's very
easy for the eye to follow the

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:09.920
flow of information.

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:11.320
OK, moving on.

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:13.740
I think the next step is one
of the biggest, and this is

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:17.860
something we've touched on a
million times in the show, but

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:19.040
typography.

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:21.630
In a moment you'll see the
difference that just a few

00:10:21.630 --> 00:10:28.560
attributes can make in the
overall visual aesthetic, but

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:31.290
also just the ease in consuming
information.

00:10:31.290 --> 00:10:34.245
So let's go to the next
section on typography.

00:10:34.245 --> 00:10:36.790
So you'll notice that here--

00:10:36.790 --> 00:10:39.720
and this is more like micro
typography, where we've looked

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:41.710
at the treatment of text at the

00:10:41.710 --> 00:10:44.060
individual character level.

00:10:44.060 --> 00:10:47.750
I guess it's a combination of
macro and micro, macro being

00:10:47.750 --> 00:10:52.620
the typography that's creating
the general figures of text,

00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:54.360
the general blocks of text.

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:57.660
In this case, we've looked at
the micro aspect of that.

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:01.880
So if we look in here to the
list screen, you'll notice

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:06.430
that in each of the articles,
the title stands

00:11:06.430 --> 00:11:07.360
out a little more.

00:11:07.360 --> 00:11:10.160
It's Roboto Bold Condensed.

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:14.530
And the subtitle, the "18
minutes ago by the author,"

00:11:14.530 --> 00:11:18.040
that was made more muted since
that's less important

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:18.830
information.

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:22.690
Once your eye settles on a title
that you want to read

00:11:22.690 --> 00:11:25.260
about, maybe at that point, you
then want to read about

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:27.470
the subtitle or you want to
find out who wrote that.

00:11:27.470 --> 00:11:30.350
And so once your eye settles
on the title, then you can

00:11:30.350 --> 00:11:33.000
make the small visual step to
look at who wrote it and when

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.120
it was published.

00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:37.910
But this really cleanly
separates each individual

00:11:37.910 --> 00:11:41.570
title from the subtitle
as well.

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:45.500
And then on the detail screen
here, we've used a similar

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:46.830
treatment for the title here.

00:11:46.830 --> 00:11:51.890
We've again used Roboto
Condensed Bold.

00:11:51.890 --> 00:11:56.570
But then for the text itself,
we've actually used a custom

00:11:56.570 --> 00:11:59.000
font, it's called Rosario.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.230
But this is generally
not necessary to

00:12:01.230 --> 00:12:01.960
use a custom font.

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:04.580
You can use one of the Roboto
variants for body text.

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:08.100
But we found that in this case,
it may be possible to

00:12:08.100 --> 00:12:12.190
introduce this custom font in
a light way, not using it

00:12:12.190 --> 00:12:16.190
overly throughout the UI, not
making every single UI element

00:12:16.190 --> 00:12:17.340
this custom font.

00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:21.510
But in this case, it may
improve legibility.

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:25.480
So any thoughts on the
typography, guys?

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:26.260
NICK BUTCHER: You want to
talk about the line

00:12:26.260 --> 00:12:28.090
spacing as well at all?

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:28.420
ROMAN NURIK: Sure.

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:32.300
So another important aspect
you should look at, when

00:12:32.300 --> 00:12:36.900
changing fonts especially,
is the line spacing.

00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:39.440
In typography terms,
it's the leading.

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:42.490
It's basically the space
between each line.

00:12:42.490 --> 00:12:45.440
And this affects, again, that
readability aspect.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:49.410
How easy is it for the eye to
move from one line to the next

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:52.120
as you get to the end of one
line, jumping over to the next

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:53.340
one and starting that?

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:56.620
So all these things-- the
spacing around the text, the

00:12:56.620 --> 00:12:59.090
line spacing between each
line-- that's all very

00:12:59.090 --> 00:13:00.700
important to the readability.

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:03.780
And so here we've used I think
a multiplier of 1.2.

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:06.340
But generally, if you feel that
your text is a little too

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:11.430
cramped, don't underestimate the
power of introducing a 1.1

00:13:11.430 --> 00:13:14.250
or 1.2 line spacing.

00:13:14.250 --> 00:13:16.490
ADAM KOCH: And from the
development side, there's two

00:13:16.490 --> 00:13:17.940
attributes generally that you
want to look at here.

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:20.510
It's Android Family and
Android Line Spacing

00:13:20.510 --> 00:13:21.890
Multiplier.

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:26.541
So those together allow you to
achieve an effect like this.

00:13:26.541 --> 00:13:29.070
ROMAN NURIK: And I should
mention that for custom

00:13:29.070 --> 00:13:32.530
fonts-- and again, use them very
sparingly in key areas

00:13:32.530 --> 00:13:35.530
where it may improve the
experience for reading large

00:13:35.530 --> 00:13:38.360
blocks of text.

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:39.930
For custom typefaces,
you may want to look

00:13:39.930 --> 00:13:41.200
at Google Web Fonts.

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:43.990
Rosario, for example, is
available through Google Web

00:13:43.990 --> 00:13:46.870
Fonts and it hints really,
really well on mobile.

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:49.410
So that's another key important
thing is you've got

00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:51.450
to make sure to not just pick a
font based on what it looks

00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:52.310
like on the web.

00:13:52.310 --> 00:13:54.410
You want to actually try it out
on a few devices, and make

00:13:54.410 --> 00:13:56.260
sure that it looks
really crisp.

00:13:56.260 --> 00:14:00.690
Because some fonts, some TTF
files, don't actually have

00:14:00.690 --> 00:14:03.840
really good hinting
instructions, and so when

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:07.740
they're taken down to smaller
sizes, they're not going to

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:08.380
look very good.

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:10.150
They're just going to
kind of be off and

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:12.010
not very well aligned.

00:14:12.010 --> 00:14:13.630
So that's something that is
definitely important to try,

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:18.440
and not just on the web
but on mobile as well.

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:19.690
Shall we move on?

00:14:19.690 --> 00:14:21.550
NICK BUTCHER: Well, I just want
to say, I think the use

00:14:21.550 --> 00:14:23.710
of different font weights is
a very good way for giving

00:14:23.710 --> 00:14:24.850
structure to your content.

00:14:24.850 --> 00:14:27.190
I think exactly what Roman was
saying about how you want to

00:14:27.190 --> 00:14:29.150
make this [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:29.150 --> 00:14:32.190
18 minutes ago, see visually,
but be equally

00:14:32.190 --> 00:14:33.500
legible if you need it.

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:36.755
Just by glancing at this
screenshot, if you look away

00:14:36.755 --> 00:14:39.700
and look back, it just stands
out, the structure of the

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:41.880
content and what you want to
read first, and it's so much

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:43.400
easier to scan the page now.

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:44.930
[INAUDIBLE].

00:14:44.930 --> 00:14:45.250
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:14:45.250 --> 00:14:47.500
This concept of visual hierarchy
is very important.

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:51.560
You want to make sure to
establish a visual hierarchy

00:14:51.560 --> 00:14:54.270
in terms of, what is the top
level item and then what are

00:14:54.270 --> 00:14:55.210
its sub-items?

00:14:55.210 --> 00:14:57.620
In this case, the top level
item is the title.

00:14:57.620 --> 00:15:01.430
The title of the article is
basically the name that you

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:05.040
would put in the tree
for the article.

00:15:05.040 --> 00:15:06.640
That would be its title.

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:10.600
So the subtitle, as well as its
body content, is kind of a

00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:14.450
child of that, so that should
be lower in the visual

00:15:14.450 --> 00:15:16.390
hierarchy, so it should stand
out a little less.

00:15:16.390 --> 00:15:19.640
Again, once your eye hits the
title, then it could move on

00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:24.190
to the sub-items in that tree
to go ahead and read details

00:15:24.190 --> 00:15:26.462
about that.

00:15:26.462 --> 00:15:29.330
All right, moving on?

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:32.400
So alternatively, we actually
created an alternative

00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:33.030
presentation.

00:15:33.030 --> 00:15:35.640
This is something that doesn't
work in every case.

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:37.190
And I think in this case
actually, it doesn't work

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:37.720
super well.

00:15:37.720 --> 00:15:41.490
But alternatively, you could
combine photos and text.

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:45.260
This is something that a couple
of popular apps do now.

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:47.420
But what you could do is combine
photos and text.

00:15:47.420 --> 00:15:50.920
Just make sure that, again,
your text lines up.

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:55.600
So here you'll notice that the
title still lines up with the

00:15:55.600 --> 00:15:58.620
subtitle, and it lines up
with the body as well.

00:15:58.620 --> 00:16:00.770
So that's, again, very important
to establish those

00:16:00.770 --> 00:16:02.020
clear lines for alignment.

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:05.950
NICK BUTCHER: So have you used
a visual treatment behind the

00:16:05.950 --> 00:16:08.360
text here to give it some
contrast because you don't

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:10.110
control the image?

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:10.590
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:16:10.590 --> 00:16:12.560
So there's a little
bit here in the

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:13.970
sense of we use a gradient.

00:16:13.970 --> 00:16:17.570
We've shown this in the past
with, I think it was

00:16:17.570 --> 00:16:18.950
TripAdvisor's redesign.

00:16:18.950 --> 00:16:22.380
Nick, you used that effect.

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:27.340
We used a gradient, a light
black gradient.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:33.250
So it fades from about a 30%
or 40% opaque black to 0%

00:16:33.250 --> 00:16:37.040
opaque black so that content
along the bottom has stronger

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:38.350
background protection.

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:40.130
So if the image itself--

00:16:40.130 --> 00:16:42.600
let's say this image of a
steak-- if the whole image is

00:16:42.600 --> 00:16:46.150
actually white, then you'll
still be able to read the text

00:16:46.150 --> 00:16:49.190
because of that background
protection.

00:16:49.190 --> 00:16:53.120
So since we're running sort of
low on time, let's start

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:54.440
flying through some of these.

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:58.200
So we also added a ViewPager
to make sure that you can

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:00.730
swipe between the
detail screens.

00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:02.880
This is fairly straightforward
using the ViewPager from

00:17:02.880 --> 00:17:04.579
Support Library.

00:17:04.579 --> 00:17:06.220
NICK BUTCHER: It's [INAUDIBLE]
is well documented on the

00:17:06.220 --> 00:17:08.140
design side.

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:10.510
ROMAN NURIK: And you should,
